## Learn: Isosceles Triangle Theorems

### Key Concept: Base Angles Theorem

If two sides of a triangle are congruent, then the angles opposite those sides are congruent.

In isosceles △ABC with \(\overline{AB} \cong \overline{AC}\):

[
\angle B \cong \angle C
]

### Key Concept: Converse

If two angles of a triangle are congruent, then the sides opposite those angles are congruent.

[
\angle B \cong \angle C \implies \overline{AB} \cong \overline{AC}
]

---

## Learn: Equilateral Triangle Properties

### Key Concept

If a triangle is equilateral, then it is equiangular. Each angle measures 60°.

[
\text{Equilateral} \iff \text{Equiangular}
]

An equilateral triangle is also isosceles (since it satisfies the condition of having at least two congruent sides).

---

## Example 1 — Find Base Angles of an Isosceles Triangle

An isosceles triangle has a vertex angle of 40°. Find the measure of each base angle.

### Step 1: Set Up the Equation

Let each base angle = \(x\).

The vertex angle is between the two congruent legs, so the base angles are the two equal angles.

[
40° + x + x = 180°
]

### Step 2: Solve

[
40° + 2x = 180°
]
[
2x = 140°
]
[
x = 70°
]

### Step 3: Verify

[
40° + 70° + 70° = 180° \checkmark
]

✅ Answer: Each base angle is 70°.

---

## Example 2 — Find the Vertex Angle

In an isosceles triangle, each base angle measures 55°. Find the vertex angle.

### Step 1: Set Up the Equation

Let the vertex angle = \(v\).

[
v + 55° + 55° = 180°
]

### Step 2: Solve

[
v + 110° = 180°
]
[
v = 70°
]

### Step 3: Verify

[
70° + 55° + 55° = 180° \checkmark
]

✅ Answer: The vertex angle is 70°.

