## Example 4 — Prove Base Angles Are Congruent

**Given:** \(\overline{AB} \cong \overline{AC}\) in △ABC.

**Prove:** \(\angle B \cong \angle C\).

### Step 1: Plan the Proof

Draw the angle bisector from \(A\) to \(\overline{BC}\) at point \(D\). This creates two smaller triangles. Prove the triangles congruent, then use CPCTC.

### Step 2: Two-Column Proof

| Statement | Reason |
|-----------|--------|
| 1. \(\overline{AB} \cong \overline{AC}\) | 1. Given |
| 2. Draw \(\overline{AD}\) so it bisects \(\angle A\) | 2. An angle bisector can be constructed |
| 3. \(\angle BAD \cong \angle CAD\) | 3. Definition of angle bisector |
| 4. \(\overline{AD} \cong \overline{AD}\) | 4. Reflexive Property |
| 5. △ABD ≅ △ACD | 5. SAS (steps 1, 3, 4) |
| 6. \(\angle B \cong \angle C\) | 6. CPCTC |

### Step 3: Interpretation

By constructing the angle bisector and proving the two resulting triangles congruent by SAS, we can conclude that the base angles are congruent.

✅ Answer: \(\angle B \cong \angle C\) proved using the Base Angles Theorem.

