## Example 6 — Real-World Application: Equilateral Roof Truss

An architect designs a roof truss in the shape of an equilateral triangle. Each side of the truss is 16 feet. Find the angles of the truss and the height from the base to the peak.

### Step 1: Angles

An equilateral triangle is equiangular, so each angle is 60°.

### Step 2: Find the Height

Drop a perpendicular from the peak to the base. This bisects the base into two segments of 8 ft each and creates two 30-60-90 right triangles.

Using the Pythagorean theorem:

[
h^2 + 8^2 = 16^2
]
[
h^2 + 64 = 256
]
[
h^2 = 192
]
[
h = \sqrt{192} = \sqrt{64 \times 3} = 8\sqrt{3} \approx 13.86 \text{ ft}
]

### Step 3: Verify

In a 30-60-90 triangle with short leg 8, the long leg should be \(8\sqrt{3}\). ✓

✅ Answer: Each angle is 60°, and the height is \(8\sqrt{3} \approx 13.86\) feet.

